<span id="freeTextContainer400311522185927429">This is an oddly perfect book about Scott&apos;s trip to the South Pole.<br/>There are five sections, each one written in the voice of one the men making the final journey.<br/>The perspective keeps shifting, and it&apos;s left to the reader to try and work out the &apos;true&apos; nature of the expedition. Was it an act of folly? A piece of heroism? Or both?<br/>I love Beryl Bainbridge&apos;s work because she dispenses with so many conventions. The only &apos;plot&apos; is the story of the journey itself. And like the journey there are unexpec</span>
  <span id="freeText400311522185927429" style="display:none">This is an oddly perfect book about Scott's trip to the South Pole.<br />There are five sections, each one written in the voice of one the men making the final journey.<br />The perspective keeps shifting, and it's left to the reader to try and work out the 'true' nature of the expedition. Was it an act of folly? A piece of heroism? Or both?<br />I love Beryl Bainbridge's work because she dispenses with so many conventions. The only 'plot' is the story of the journey itself. And like the journey there are unexpected turns, digressions.<br />But not a word is wasted.....</span>
